article.headline: Gugliotta 3 gives Utah momentum
article.linkText: Jazz rally to snap 4-game home losing skid
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Utah Jazz appeared headed for their fifth straight home loss until the newest member of the team hit his only shot of the night. It turned out to be a big one. Standing more than two yards behind the 3-point line with the shot clock about to expire, Tom Gugliotta made a shot that cut a six-point deficit in half and started a Jazz rally toward a 99-86 win over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday. "I kind of had to take it," said Gugliotta, whose only field goal of the game started a 14-0 run to end Utah's home losing streak. Gugliotta didn't have a 3-pointer in 30 games for Phoenix before getting traded to the Jazz at the deadline last Thursday. "That was really big. I didn't really think it at the time, but it was a big momentum boost for us going into that fourth," said Raja Bell, who scored 13 of his 23 points in the final quarter as Utah pulled away. "That was almost halfcourt. Man, it was impressive because he shot it like a regular jump shot." Gugliotta hadn't made a 3 since the 2001-02 season. He was 1-for-3 from the field Tuesday and finished with four points and four rebounds in 12 minutes. Andrei Kirilenko had 27 points, 10 rebounds and four blocks, and Carlos Arroyo also scored 23 with nine rebounds and five assists for the Jazz. Ray Allen scored 26 and Antonio Daniels added 22 points for the Sonics, who were outscored 26-10 in the final quarter and lost for the eighth straight time at Utah. Seattle coach Nate McMillan wasn't around to see the end, ejected with his second technical foul early in the final period. The Sonics and Jazz play again Wednesday night in Seattle. "We've got to start winning a couple," Allen said. "This is my first full year in this uniform and it's starting to get on my nerves." Seattle fell behind by 12 in the first half, then took control in the third quarter. After trailing 54-46 at halftime, the Sonics went 5-for-10 from the field and 18-for-19 from the line in the third to take the lead. Daniels scored nine straight for Seattle and put the Sonics up 76-70 on a free throw with 1:12 left in the third quarter. Utah was seconds from turning the ball over on a shot clock violation when Gugliotta started the rally with his unlikely shot that got the Jazz to 76-73 entering the final quarter. Bell opened the fourth with a field goal and the Jazz scored the next nine points before Allen finally scored for Seattle with about seven minutes remaining. That cut Utah's lead to 87-78, but the Jazz took off again as Bell scored 11 of the next 13 points. As the Sonics unraveled, so did their coach. McMillan was upset the Sonics did not get a foul call after a physical struggle for a couple of offensive rebounds. Utah was on a 9-0 run and McMillan kept talking to referee Steve Javie, who heard enough and called McMillan for his second technical with 9:14 remaining in the game. It didn't seem to inspire Seattle, which went 2-for-21 from the floor in the final quarter. "I turned around and he wasn't there," Allen said. "It wasn't any big dramatics that go along with coaches getting kicked out normally. It seemed like he just walked off the floor."

Game notes
Javie also called McMillan's first technical after the coach was upset in the first quarter when Jerome James was called for an offensive foul. James got a technical a couple minutes later for saying something to the officials while Bell was shooting a free throw. ... The Jazz have gone 24 games without scoring 100 points. They could have had it Tuesday, but slowed the offense in the final minutes with the game already decided. ... The game was delayed for a few minutes early in the fourth quarter as workers tried to dry the floor after a skit that had a blindfolded Sonics fan fall into a wading pool of whipped cream.
